          <msContents>
            <summary>A paraphrased Persian translation and commentaries of <title xml:lang="ara-Latn-x-lc">Kit&#x101;b al-&#x12B;m&#x101;n</title>, the first book of
                            the <title xml:lang="ara-Latn-x-lc">&#x1E62;a&#x1E25;&#x12B;&#x1E25; Muslim</title>&#x6A9;&#x62A;&#x627;&#x628; &#x627;&#x644;&#x627;&#x6CC;&#x645;&#x627;&#x646;
                                <title xml:lang="ara">&#x635;&#x62D;&#x64A;&#x62D; &#x645;&#x633;&#x644;&#x645;</title>or <title xml:lang="ara-Latn-x-lc">al-J&#x101;mi&#x2BF; al-&#x1E62;a&#x1E25;&#x12B;&#x1E25;</title> , the great
                            collection of traditions by <name key="n82164848" ref="http://viaf.org/viaf/90038752"><persName xml:lang="ara-Latn-x-lc" type="standard">Muslim ibn al-&#x1E24;ajj&#x101;j
                                    al-Qushayr&#x12B;, approximately 821-875</persName><persName xml:lang="ara-Latn-x-lc" type="org"/><persName xml:lang="ara" type="alt">&#x627;&#x644;&#x646;&#x633;&#x627;&#x628;&#x648;&#x631;&#x649;&#x60C; &#x627;&#x628;&#x648; &#x627;&#x644;&#x62D;&#x633;&#x64A;&#x646; &#x645;&#x633;&#x644;&#x645; &#x628;&#x646;
                                    &#x627;&#x644;&#x647;&#x62C;&#x651;&#x627;&#x62C; &#x627;&#x644;&#x642;&#x634;&#x64A;&#x631;&#x649; &#x60C;&#x200F;&#x200F;</persName></name>. Hence the title Kit&#x101;b
                            al-&#x12B;m&#x101;n attributed to the MS. by the copyist and subsequently lettered
                            in Latin. The copyist remarks, in the colophon, that it contains the
                            last part of the first section, and that it was composed in the year
                                <date calendar="Hijri-qamari">A.H. 666</date>. He does not mention
                            the name of the commentator. But he seems to have had in his disposal
                            the commentator&#x2019;s original handwritten copy, though it is in need of
                            further scrutiny as the key word to this deduction, i.e. "handwritten"
                            &#x628;&#x62E;&#x637; is covered under repair and its accuracy cannot be ascertained. The
                            commentator remains anonymous. <seg>An additional remark, though in a
                                different hand <locus from="157v" to="157v">f. 157v</locus>,
                                suggests that it has been compared with the copy written by the
                                commentator:&#x642;&#x648;&#x6CC;&#x644; &#x628;&#x6CC;&#x62F; &#x627;&#x644;&#x645;&#x648;&#x644;&#x641; &#x628;&#x642;&#x62F;&#x631; &#x627;&#x644;&#x648;&#x633;&#x639; &#x648; &#x627;&#x644;&#x627;&#x645;&#x6A9;&#x627;&#x646; &#x648; &#x627;&#x644;&#x644;&#x647; &#x627;&#x644;&#x645;&#x633;&#x62A;&#x639;&#x627;&#x646;
                            </seg> It corresponds thoroughly with "bab al-iman" from the original
                            Arabic &#x1E62;ahih of Muslim of which a complete copy is available at JRUL
                            (128 [790], ff. 5b-28a).<seg>However, it is somewhat negligently copied
                                and is variedly chapter-headed. Following the style of the
                                paraphrased sections in the original Arabic, it begins without any
                                of the usual amplificatory introductions and only two lines are
                                confined to the mention of the God&#x2019;s name and the preliminary
                                prayer. Michael Kerney finds it odd and in his hand list of Persian
                                MSS. in the JRUL suggests that "there may have been a separate
                                preface or introduction prefixed." But the completness of the first
                                octavo group of leaves of which the MS. commences on the first recto
                                page, indicates to the contrary.However, it is somewhat negligently
                                copied and is variedly chapter-headed. Following the style of the
